<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x000b_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vidence from Rail Freight Group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (SRN 002</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rail Freight Group (RFG) is pleased to provide evidence to the Transport Committee Inquiry into the Strategic Road Network.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RFG is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">representative body for rail freight in the UK.  We represent over 100 member companies who are active all across the rail freight sector, including train operators, customers, ports, terminal operators, suppliers, and support services.  Our aim is to incr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ease the volume of goods moved by rail, to deliver environmental and economic benefits to the UK.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the context of this Inquiry, we note that many of our member companies are also active road freight operators.  Our response does not cover any specific p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oints on the strategic road network other than where there is relationship with rail freight.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">General Comments </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For customers and operators in the road and rail freight sector, the different modes are generally viewed as being in competition.  Indeed, f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or specific movements there is little doubt that this is the case, with road and rail (and in some cases) water competing for traffic on cost and on quality.  Rail freight must equal or better road costs if it is to win, and retain, business.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a national perspective, and in consideration of new infrastructure, it is necessary to consider how freight can be moved most efficiently for the overall benefit of the UK.  We would argue that this requires each mode to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to play to its streng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ths, and that the development of each mode is considered in parallel when looking at particular interventions.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although many of the measures in the Strategic Roads White Paper may be reasonable, there is little evidence that they have been considered as p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">art of an overall national strategy for efficient freight movement considering all modes holistically.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Specific Questions</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Q2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are pleased that the Highways Age</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncy is starting to develop route based strategies for the strategic road network.  This approach has worked well for the rail industry, with the programme of Route Utilisation Strategies which have been developed over the last decade – now being replaced b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y the Long Term Planning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Process studies.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, we think that there should be much closer align</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment the development of route based strategies, and investment in the rail network. This would allow consideration of how investment in rail could help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meet the demands of the road corridor, and also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highlight where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">investment in roads might in some cases undermine the case for rail freight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> compensating measures.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This approach was used to some extent on the A14 corridor where the research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">studies showed how investment in the parallel rail corridor could help accommodate some of the predicted HGV growth.  The Atkins A14 Study Output 3 report stated that ‘p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lanned investment in rail route from Felixstowe could cut HGV traffic on A14 by 11%, wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ich is 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0-80% of forecast growth in HGVs’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This has helped to support the case for investment in the Felixstowe to Nuneaton rail corridor which was confirmed in last summer’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">High Level Output Specification, and is expected to be delivered over the next </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">five years.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although it is not a matter for the Westminster </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parliament, we have been raising concerns over the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£3bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> upgrade of the A9 in Scotland which is planned without any parallel investment in the rail network between Perth and Inverness.  T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his risks undermining both potential growth and existing rail traffic on the corridor, factors which appear not to be included in the assessment of the scheme. We are pressing for the rail freight needs to be an integral part of the assessment and funding.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would therefore urge for more cross-modal assessment to be undertaken in the development of the route strategies including the A1 and Trans-Pennine routes where study work is already under development.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are also concerned that much of the current i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nitiatives being progressed by DfT are focussed on the long distance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">haulage of goods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where rail freight is best able</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to compete with road.  Instead, we consider developments may be better targetted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at areas where road haulage has a natural monopoly,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as specific deliveries and access away from the main trunk rail network.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, the longer semi trailer trial, presently underway, targets the long distance market in particular, and will make it more difficult for rail to compete.  Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT’s assessment suggested that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etween 27% to 32% of the environmental benefits of longer trailers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are assumed to be gained by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> running fewer trains. By 2025,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 84% of the industry operational savings would be from lower rail costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  In other words, a signif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">icant proportion of the benefit cited from longer semi trailers came at the expense of rail freight.  DfT are now progressing research into 10 lorry convoys – yet the average train removes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40-50</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the road.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT are presently also reviewing the rail freight grant scheme, which exists to balance the different costs of road and rail freight where the environmental benefits justify it.  The de facto grant rate has fallen significantly since the scheme was introdu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ced, as rail has improved its efficiency, network investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been progressed and economies of scale have risen.  However, particularly for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">domestic traffic in the retail sector, and shorter distance intermodal port traffic, the need for grant is expect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed to remain, and we will be urging Government to ensure that the scheme continues and is appropriately funded.  Measures such as longer semi trailers also perpetuate the need for grant.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recognise that DfT has provided investment in the rail network in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> support of rail freight, and that all modes need to progress and seek efficiencies.  However </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there should be a balanced approach to enable the most efficient and environmentally friendly solution for the UK.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Q4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> can we improve the reliability and eff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">iciency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Encouraging a greater use of rail freight will have benefits for the strategic road network.  We note, for example, the proposed studies of lorry convoys of up to 10 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, yet the average freight train can take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40-50</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lorries off the road.  Encouraging rail freight can also help improve road safety again by removing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the road.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rail freight is acknowledged as having a superior environmental performance, pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ducing around 70% less carbon dioxide than the equivalent journey by road.  Rail’s environmental credentials will be further improved if a greater use can be made of electric traction in the future.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK? </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new HGV charge applied to foreign registered hauliers appears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unlikely to make any significant contribution to road funding.  We would support a longer term move to a distance based charge, common in other EU countries, which provides the right incentives for modal shift, encourages reductions in road miles and more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closely aligns the charging structure for road and rail.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>